instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The incubator DT is orchestrated around a RabbitMQ message broker that mediates communication between physical and cyber components. Low‑level driver abstracts sensor and actuator I/O and publishes measurements to RabbitMQ; the controller (a bang‑bang logic) consumes these measurements, issues fan and heat‑bed commands, and publishes its control states. Separate DT services—real‑time visualisation (using a time‑series database and dashboard), on‑demand model calibration, Kalman‑filter based anomaly detection, and co‑simulation for what‑if analysis—are implemented as independent processes subscribing to the same message bus, achieving loose coupling and coordinated operation. Calibration updates model parameters used by monitors and the Kalman filter, while the self‑adaptation loop (detect‑plan‑execute) closes the coordination across components."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is governed by four explicit assumptions: (1) uniform temperature distribution inside the box (ensured by the fan), (2) negligible heat accumulation in the box walls, (3) constant specific heat capacity of air, and (4) all electrical power converted to heat in the air (relaxed in Model B). Validation experiments demonstrated that Model B better predicts the heat‑bed’s thermal inertia, confirming higher fidelity for that aspect. Calibration algorithms continuously adjust model parameters using measured sensor data to reduce prediction error. Uncertainty sources include the simplifying assumptions, variations in ambient temperature, and unmodeled heat losses. Anomaly detection is performed by a Kalman filter that compares measured temperatures with Model B predictions, flagging deviations as potential faults. Quality assurance is achieved through on‑demand calibration, continuous monitoring, and re‑validation of models when anomalies are detected."
]

